Management of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany
Scrutiny report
Preface
Taxes are the main source of revenue for public budgets.
The work of the Court of Auditors should therefore focus on examining this area.
This applies in particular to VAT fraud.
This alone would result in an estimated EUR 100 billion in annual tax losses in the European Union1.
At the Sixth EUROSAI Congress in Bonn in 2005, participants stressed the need for enhanced cooperation.
This allows auditors, for example, to exchange audit approaches and optimise audit practice.
VAT is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.
In 2006, the courts of auditors of both states examined UST in parallel for the first time.
The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.
Given that UST is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between audit bodies is needed to assess fully whether the measures taken are appropriate to effectively counter UST fraud.
The two audit bodies decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit.
