4.1 Implementation of the recommendations of the first joint review
4.1.1 Implementation of the recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of the conditions for the registration of taxable persons within the EU
to the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors recommended adapting the requirements for VAT registration and introducing new rules for cancelling registration in CZ.
These changed rules should more effectively contain the risk of possible tax evasion.
In certain cases, it was found that the tax authorities did not remove the VAT registration of taxable persons if they failed to fulfil their obligations under Czech Law No 235/2004 (hereinafter referred to as the "USt Law").
So far, the Czech finance ministry has not submitted a revision to require the Fx to delete if taxpayers repeatedly fail to file UST declarations.
Under the Czech UST Act, if (a) the taxable person has not made any transactions for twelve consecutive months and the FA has not informed the reasons for this, the taxable person has failed to fulfil his duties under the UST Act; (c) the taxable person no longer meets the conditions for tax liability.
The initial investigation showed that due to the existing legal situation, the FA Prague 1 must delete USt registration of "foreign taxpayers"3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year if they were not obliged to register and pay USt in the current calendar year.
The FA Prague 1 often did not delete the UST registration of these taxpayers because the relevant provision of the deadline could not be adequately implemented in practice.
The issue was resolved by the amendment of the UST Act, which took effect on January 1, 2009.
This gives the IFA the power to cancel a foreign taxable person's registration if he has not provided taxable or exempt goods or services entitled to deduction in the previous calendar year.
Recommendation 2
ZM's monthly levy
As a result of the initial audit, the audit bodies had recommended that ZM's monthly levy be introduced.
The Council Directive, which shortened the ZM levy to one month, was implemented in the CZ by the UST Act which entered into force on January 1, 2010.
The ZM must now be delivered electronically.
Furthermore, a CCM must be issued when services whose place of performance is to be determined under Section 9(1) of the UST Act are provided to a person registered as liable for VAT in another Member State.
This obligation stems from Council Directive 2008/8/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC as regards the place of supply of services.
