4.4 Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
4.4.1 Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic
The legislation on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims in the EU is essentially based on:
Council Directive 76/308/EEC on mutual assistance for the recovery of claims arising from measures included in the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund and levies and customs duties;
Council Directive 2001/44/EC amending Council Directive 76/308/EEC on mutual assistance for the recovery of claims relating to measures forming part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, levies and duties, and concerning VAT and certain excise duties, and
Commission Directive 2002/94/EC laying down detailed implementing rules for certain articles of Directive 76/308/EEC on mutual assistance for the recovery of claims relating to certain levies, duties, taxes and other measures.
The CZ implemented Council Directive 76/308/EEC by Law No 252/2000 on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims.
Once Council Directive 2001/44/EC had been adopted, it had to be transposed into Czech law.
In this context, the legislative amendment No 191/2004 on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims was adopted.
A new relevant piece of legislation was adopted by Commission Regulation (EC) No 1179/2008 of 28 November 2008.
The annexes to this regulation contain new application forms to be used from 1 January 2009, making electronic transmission mandatory and requiring the requesting authority to certify the conformity of all documents sent with the original.
The main principles of international mutual assistance for the recovery of claims are:
1. the principle of reciprocity applies;
2. mutual assistance must always be provided only on request and when fulfilling all the conditions;
3. mutual assistance does not cover claims which are considered a criminal sanction in the requested State;
4. the procedure for intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of claims must be carried out in accordance with the national law of the requested State;
5. In the recovery procedure, foreign claims do not take precedence over domestic claims;
6. mutual assistance is provided only for the recovery of uncontested claims;
7. The principle of exhaustion applies: the requesting State shall use all means to recover the claim under national law.
Law No 191/2004 provides for three forms of mutual assistance: provision of information, notification of acts and actual collection.
Procedures for outgoing requests to other EU Member States
The competent FA shall submit the request for information, the request for notification of legal acts or the request for recovery, together with the relevant documents, electronically to the Ministry of Finance of the CZ.
The Ministry of Finance of the CZ translates the request into the language concerned, scans it with all installations and transmits it via the communication network or the CCN/CSI interface of the relevant fiscal authority of the State concerned.
A request for recovery assistance must meet the following condition: the claim must exceed EUR 1 500 and must not exceed five years.
The requested authority may refuse recovery if the requirements are not met.
Procedures for incoming requests from other Member States
The CZ Ministry of Finance must confirm the receipt of requests from other Member States within seven days at the latest.
If it decides not to grant the request, it must inform the requesting authority of the reasons for refusal, specifying the specific provisions of the Directive on which it is based.
The notification must be sent no later than three months after the receipt date of the request.
After receiving the request, the Treasury is examining whether the request meets all legal requirements.
After this, it will send the request to the relevant FA through the relevant financial directorate. If the recovery request is granted, the FA will have to determine, among other things, the debtor's assets, e.g. by extracts from the land register, enquiry into existing bank accounts and registration of cars with the registration office.
After six months from the date of receipt of the request, the Ministry of Finance shall inform the CZ of the outcome of the investigation.
The requesting authority must also be informed if the taxable persons concerned cannot be reached and the claim cannot therefore be recovered.
All amounts successfully recovered must be transferred to the requesting authority within one month of recovery.
With the consent of the requesting State, the Czech FA can agree on the claim for hours or instalments.
The interest or default surcharges imposed on the debtor for the delay period pursuant to Law No 337/1992 on the management of taxes and fees
stand by the requesting State.
In particular, in 2006 and 2007, the CZ Ministry of Finance delayed sending the relevant FA the recovery requests received.
The same was true for the forwarding of the recovery requests made by the Czech fx to the competent authority in the requested state.
The investigation found that the Ministry of Finance had breached the law on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of claims by failing to inform the competent authority of the requesting Member State of the state of play of the recovery procedure within six months of confirmation of receipt of the request.
The situation has improved since 2008.
