4.4.2 Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in Germany
The legal basis for intergovernmental assistance in tax matters is Council Directive 2008/55/EC of 26 May 2008 (EC Recovery Directive)14 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1178/2008 of 28 November 2008 (EC Implementing Directive).
With a view to improving legibility and clarity, the EC Directive codified Council Directive 76/308/EEC of 15 March 1976.
These include the recovery of UST and taxes on income and assets, including related interest, fees and default surcharges.
The EC Recovery Directive was transposed into German law by the Recovery Act (EC)17 of 3 May 2003.
The enforcement procedure in Germany is governed by the Levy Order (AO).
Section 117(2) AO provides that financial authorities may provide intergovernmental legal and administrative assistance in accordance with international treaties and legal standards applicable in national law.
Part six of the AO (section 249-346) contains the legislation for enforcement proceedings.
The administrative action of the financial authorities regulates in particular the execution and enforcement order.
The Federal Ministry of Finance agreed with the representatives of the Supreme Financial Authorities of the Länder on the principles of mutual assistance in tax matters and transferred its own jurisdiction in this area to the Federal Central Office for Taxation18.
General conditions for the admissibility of a recovery assistance request are:
- the legal requirements must be met (Section 251, 254 AO).
All domestic means of recovery have been exhausted.
The claims for which assistance is requested are indisputable.
The period between the issuing of the enforcement order or the date on which the claim or title became unchallengeable and the date of the request may not exceed five years.
The claim must be at least EUR 1 500.
Procedures for Outgoing Requests to Other EU Member States German Requests for Recovery of Backdated Taxes are forwarded by the enforcement bodies of the Fx through the competent central authority and the Federal Central Office for Taxation of the Foreign Authority concerned, e.g. the Czech CLO.
Details are set out in the "Intergovernmental Assistance in Tax Collection" leaflet of 19 January 2004.
This leaflet is currently being revised by a federal-state working group and adapted to the new Recovery Directive.
The request is also forwarded electronically from the FA to the central authority.
The latter checks whether it is correct in substance and form.
If not, the request will be returned to the FA concerned.
Otherwise, it will be sent to the Federal Central Office for Taxation.
The Federal Central Office for Taxation then takes over the necessary communication with the foreign authority concerned.
Procedures for receiving enquiries from other EU Member States
Recovery requests from other Member States are recorded in the Federal Central Office for Taxation, which sends an receipt within ten days.
It is also examining whether the formal conditions have been met.
In principle, the Federal Central Office for Taxation passes these requests on to the central authority, which allocates them to the FA and monitors the execution.
The Federal Central Office for Taxation also sends interim or final reports.
If a request lasts longer than six months, it reminds the central authority of the obligation to provide an interim report under Article 16 of Commission Directive 2002/94/EC.
After examining the formal and factual conditions for the admissibility of the request, the enforcement bodies announce relevant measures.
All amounts recovered must be transferred to the bank account specified in the request within one month of receipt.
