4.4.4 Comparison and Evaluation
All EU Member States have to comply with EU rules on mutual assistance.
The procedures for processing requests are therefore similar in the CZ and Germany.
The two Member States submitted statistics to the European Commission between 2006 and 2008.
Disagreements were striking.
In its 200620 report, the European Commission recommended that Member States produce their statistics with greater care.
In 2009, the Commission concluded that, despite a large number of requests for assistance, the inconsistencies in the statistics had decreased.
Both Court of Auditors considers it useful to have another discussion at EU level on statistics in order to avoid the remaining discrepancies.
If this does not happen, the statistics are meaningful and cannot be used for comparisons.
In addition, the Court considers that the statistics should show both the annual number of requests and the type of claims (e.g. UST, income tax) and the amounts collected per Member State.
By analysing the statistics provided by Member States, the Commission could help Member States assess their measures to combat UST fraud.
As the recovery rate per Member State can be calculated, the Court argues that Member States with low rates should aim for at least the average recovery rate within the EU.
At the request of a Member State, the Commission could play an active role.
The Foreign Recovery Requests received by the Ministry of Finance CZ were delayed in 2006 and 2007 in particular.
The same applies to the recovery requests made by the Czech fx.
The investigation showed that the Czech Ministry of Finance was in breach of Law No 191/2004 on Intergovernmental Recovery Assistance by failing to inform the competent authority of the requesting Member State of the progress of the recovery measures within the six-month period from the receipt of the request.
4.5 VAT audit at large farms
4.5.1 Value-added tax audit at large farms in the Czech Republic
General
The taxation procedure for large companies is subject to the same rules as for other taxpayers.
The assessment of large enterprises is regulated by Czech Law No 337/1992, the "Tax and Fee Management Law".
The Czech Ministry of Finance defines large enterprises as natural persons who have established a business or legal entities established to carry out a business and whose net turnover for the relevant tax period is at least CZK 2 billion, according to income and corporate tax declarations.
The taxable person is classified as a large company on the basis of the turnover value of income or corporate tax returns during the relevant tax period; for the first time in 2003.
A natural or legal person is no longer held as a large company for the purposes of turnover taxation if for three consecutive periods their net turnover during the taxation period is less than CZK 2 billion.
A taxable person can only be removed from the list of large companies if at least one type of tax has been assessed for a tax period.
All large farms were audited at least every five years until the end of 2009.
Since 2010, taxable persons have to be assessed in writing at least every two years.
The audits by the fx are intended to have the emphasis on at least one type of tax; they typically include multiple taxation periods.
The taxable large undertakings were audited by the special audit bodies or audit services of the competent body, which had been set up for a total of 13 Fx.
A special audit body carried out audits in its local area of responsibility according to the guidelines of the head of the finance directorate.
